<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Art and Craft of India</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="output.css">
    <script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
</head>

<body class="bg-gray-100 text-gray-800">

    <!-- Header Section -->
    <header class="bg-blue-800 text-white py-6">
        <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
            <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center">Art and Craft of India</h1>
        </div>
    </header>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <main class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">

        <!-- Section 1: Madhubani Painting -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="odisi.jpg" alt="Madhubani Painting" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Madhubani Painting - The Art of Mithila</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Madhubani painting, also known as Mithila art, is a traditional Indian painting style that
                        originated in the Mithila region of Bihar. This art form is characterized by intricate patterns
                        and vibrant colors, depicting scenes from mythology and nature.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2: Pashmina Shawls -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Pashmina Shawls - The Luxury of Kashmir</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Pashmina shawls, crafted from the finest wool of the Pashmina goat, are known for their softness
                        and warmth. These shawls are hand-woven by skilled artisans in Kashmir, making them a symbol of
                        luxury and elegance.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Pashmina Shawls" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 3: Warli Painting -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Warli Painting" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Warli Painting - The Tribal Art of Maharashtra</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Warli painting is a tribal art form practiced by the Warli tribe of Maharashtra. This art is
                        characterized by simple geometric shapes and patterns that depict scenes of daily life, rituals,
                        and nature.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 4: Blue Pottery -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Blue Pottery - The Craft of Jaipur</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Blue pottery, a traditional craft of Jaipur, is known for its distinctive blue glaze. This art
                        form uses a unique technique that involves mixing quartz with other ingredients to create
                        beautiful pottery pieces with intricate designs.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Blue Pottery" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 5: Tanjore Painting -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Tanjore Painting" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Tanjore Painting - The Jewel of South India</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Tanjore painting, originating from Tamil Nadu, is known for its rich colors and intricate
                        details. These paintings often depict Hindu gods and goddesses, with gold foil used to enhance
                        the grandeur of the artwork.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 6: Phulkari -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Phulkari - The Embroidery of Punjab</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Phulkari is a traditional embroidery technique from Punjab, known for its vibrant patterns and
                        colorful designs. This craft is often used to create shawls, dupattas, and other garments,
                        reflecting the rich cultural heritage of the region.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Phulkari" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 7: Channapatna Toys -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Channapatna Toys" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Channapatna Toys - The Craft of Karnataka</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Channapatna toys, made from ivory wood, are a traditional craft of Karnataka. These colorful and
                        eco-friendly toys are hand-painted using natural dyes, making them popular among children and
                        collectors alike.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 8: Kutch Embroidery -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Kutch Embroidery - The Vibrant Art of Gujarat</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Kutch embroidery, known for its bold colors and intricate designs, is a traditional craft of
                        Gujarat. This art form is often used to create garments, wall hangings, and other decorative
                        items, showcasing the cultural diversity of the region.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Kutch Embroidery" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 9: Pattachitra -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Pattachitra" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Pattachitra - The Scroll Paintings of Odisha</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Pattachitra, a traditional scroll painting from Odisha, is known for its intricate details and
                        mythological themes. These paintings are made on cloth or dried palm leaves, using natural colors
                        to create vibrant and expressive art.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 10: Kalamkari -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Kalamkari - The Pen Art of Andhra Pradesh</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Kalamkari, an ancient art form of Andhra Pradesh, involves hand-painting or block-printing on
                        fabric using natural dyes. The art often depicts epics, mythology, and nature, with intricate
                        details and vibrant colors.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Kalamkari" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 11: Bidriware -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Bidriware" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Bidriware - The Metal Craft of Karnataka</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Bidriware is a unique metal craft from Karnataka, known for its intricate silver inlay work on a
                        blackened alloy of zinc and copper. The craft is used to create various decorative items such as
                        vases, trays, and jewelry boxes, reflecting the rich cultural heritage of the region.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 12: Dhokra Craft -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-4">Dhokra Craft - The Lost Wax Art of Chhattisgarh</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Dhokra craft, practiced by the tribal communities of Chhattisgarh, is a traditional metal
                        casting technique that uses the lost wax method. This ancient art form is used to create
                        sculptures, figurines, and jewelry, showcasing the tribal culture and traditions of India.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Dhokra Craft" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

    </main>

    <!-- Footer Section -->
    <footer class="bg-gray-800 text-white py-6">
        <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center">
            <p>&copy; 2024 Cultural Heritage of India. All rights reserved.</p>
        </div>
    </footer>

</body>

</html>
